{{draft}}


{{Infobox religious building
| type = Shinto
| cult_centre = {{ill|Awata Shrine|ja|粟田神社}}<br>
[[Yasaka Shrine]]<br>
{{ill|Katano-jinja|ja|片埜神社}}<br>
{{ill|Suga-jinja|ja|須我神社}}<br>
{{ill|Hyōsu-jinja|ja|兵主神社 (西脇市)}}
| father = [[Susanoo-no-Mikoto]]
| mother = [[Kushinadahime]]
| children = {{ill|Fuha-no-Mojikunusunu|ja|布波能母遅久奴須奴神}}
| image = Suga jinja.jpg
}}[[{{PAGENAME}}]] is a [[Shinto shrine]]<nowiki/>in [[Unnan, Shimane|Unnan]], Shimane Prefecture<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |last=DNAC |title=Suga Shrine {{!}} VISIT SHIMANE |url=http://visitshimane.com/?p=2826 |access-date=2023-10-17}}</ref>

This shrine, claimed to stand on the site of the palace Susanoo built after defeating the [[Yamata no Orochi]], enshrines [[Susanoo-no-Mikoto|Susanoo]], [[Kushinadahime]], and their son {{ill|Yashimajinumi|ja|八島士奴美神}}.<ref name=":1">{{cite web |title=第十六番 須我神社 |url=https://shinbutsu.jp/shrines-temples/sugajinja/ |access-date=2020-03-30 |website=出雲國神仏霊場を巡る旅 (Izumo-no-kuni shinbutsu reijo o meguru tabi) |publisher=社寺縁座の会 (Shaji Enza no Kai)}}</ref> Listed in the Izumo ''Fudoki'' as one of sixteen shrines in [[Ohara District, Shimane|Ōhara District]] not registered with the [[Department of Divinities]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Records of Wind and Earth: A Translation of Fudoki, with Introduction and Commentaries |publisher=Association for Asian Studies, Inc. |year=1997 |pages=153 |translator=Aoki, Michiko Y.}}</ref> According to the [[Kojiki]] it was the first Shrine in Japan<ref name=":2">{{Cite web |title=Suga Jinja Shrine（Shimane） |url=https://www.jldb.bunka.go.jp/en/location/ |access-date=2023-10-17 |website=Nationwide location database |language=en}}</ref>. It  was founded immediately after the battle when Susanoo married Kushinadahime.<ref name=":3">{{Cite web |title=Holy ground of Izumo Mythology |url=https://unnan-tatara.jp/en/midokoro-taiken/shinwa-yukari.html |access-date=2023-10-17 |website=Unnan City: The Holy Ground of TATARA Ironworks and Izumo Mythology |language=en-US}}</ref> The Shrine is seen as the birthplace of [[Waka (poetry)]].<ref name=":0" /> <ref name=":2" /><ref name=":3" /> After Susanoo wrote a poem about the surrounding area.<ref name=":3" />

